00:00:27.460 --> 00:00:28.710
PROFESSOR: Good afternoon.

00:00:30.860 --> 00:00:34.170
Congratulations for braving it
through what's now become a

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:35.780
weekly snow disaster.

00:00:35.780 --> 00:00:38.650
This week's maybe three
of them or something.

00:00:38.650 --> 00:00:39.920
My name's John Gabrieli.

00:00:39.920 --> 00:00:42.910
This is Introductory to
Psychology, 9.00.

00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:45.280
This is a course about you.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:49.720
The entire course is what do we
understand in a scientific

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:51.320
way about human nature--

00:00:51.320 --> 00:00:54.230
how people's minds work, how
people's brains work that

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:55.335
supports their mind.

00:00:55.335 --> 00:00:57.990
This entire course is about
what's a scientific way to

00:00:57.990 --> 00:01:03.210
understanding how people feel,
think, and act in the world.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:07.260
And so we're trying to say that
we constantly think you

00:01:07.260 --> 00:01:10.520
must in your everyday life think
about why do you have

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:12.280
your preferences,
your desires?

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:13.110
What's easy for you?

00:01:13.110 --> 00:01:13.890
What's hard for you?

00:01:13.890 --> 00:01:16.610
What's delightful for you?

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:18.955
Why do other people behave
the way they do?

00:01:18.955 --> 00:01:19.870
How do they think?

00:01:19.870 --> 00:01:20.470
How do they feel?

00:01:20.470 --> 00:01:23.760
And so there's a lot of realms
of this that are tough to get

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:24.650
to by science.

00:01:24.650 --> 00:01:27.630
But what we're going to focus on
this semester is where the

00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:30.860
scientific approach has shed
light in the way that we used

00:01:30.860 --> 00:01:32.840
to think about experiments
and evidence,

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:35.970
about how humans tick.

00:01:35.970 --> 00:01:38.640
And as we go through this
semester, we'll talk about the

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:42.890
brain, we'll talk a fair bit
about chapters from this book,

00:01:42.890 --> 00:01:45.860
The Man Who Mistook His Wife for
a Hat, from Oliver Sacks.

00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:48.870
It was a bestseller even when it
wasn't [? a ScienceWare ?]

00:01:48.870 --> 00:01:49.130
course.

00:01:49.130 --> 00:01:49.790
It's a great book.

00:01:49.790 --> 00:01:51.060
You'll enjoy it.

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:54.590
Short, really fun chapters.

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:56.640
We'll talk about how we perceive
the world; how we

00:01:56.640 --> 00:01:59.840
see; especially, a little bit,
how we hear; how we think; how

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:03.440
we feel; personality; how we
differ from one to the other;

00:02:03.440 --> 00:02:05.550
and what we're sort of like;
and how we behave in the

00:02:05.550 --> 00:02:09.320
world; development from
childhood and infancy through

00:02:09.320 --> 00:02:11.520
adolescence, through young
adulthood, where you are

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:16.700
mostly, through getting older,
where I am; social

00:02:16.700 --> 00:02:18.950
interaction, how we behave in
groups and think about other

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:22.740
people; and variation in
the mental health or

00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:23.780
psychopathology.

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:26.580
And increasingly, we understand
that there's a huge

00:02:26.580 --> 00:02:29.010
number of people who, at some
moment in their life or

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:33.280
another, struggle with some
aspect of mental health.

00:02:33.280 --> 00:02:35.860
And then we'll focus a lot on,
not only the psychological

00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:39.150
aspects of what we study in
terms of behavior, but also

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:41.590
the brain basis of that, and
think a little bit about to

00:02:41.590 --> 00:02:45.330
what extent the mind is what the
brain does, to what extent

00:02:45.330 --> 00:02:46.800
the mind is what
the brain does.

00:02:46.800 --> 00:02:49.940
And so for every dimension of
being a human being that we'll

00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:51.800
talk about, we'll also talk
about what we understand

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:54.150
currently from the
neurological and

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:56.660
neuroscientific literature
about how the human brain

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:58.360
supports and contributes
to different

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.150
aspects of being a person.

00:03:00.150 --> 00:03:01.200
OK.

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:05.540
So everybody who works in a
certain field thinks that

00:03:05.540 --> 00:03:08.400
their field is really, really,
really special, right?

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:10.180
So here's why psychology
is really,

00:03:10.180 --> 00:03:11.700
really, really special.

00:03:11.700 --> 00:03:15.500
So it's really, really special,
I think, most of all,

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:20.460
because every endeavor that we
undertake at a university or

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:22.250
in society as a whole--

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:24.600
it's about people, right, except
for when we think about

00:03:24.600 --> 00:03:25.340
the rest of nature.

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:29.600
But people study biology,
chemistry, and physics.

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:35.260
And they think, right, that the
sun orbits the earth for

00:03:35.260 --> 00:03:36.700
some period of time.

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:38.170
And then they think
it's the other way

00:03:38.170 --> 00:03:39.980
around currently, right?

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:42.390
OK, so people come up with
these conclusions.

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:44.740
Even though we're trying to
understand nature, it's people

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:47.510
who make certain investments
in economics or behave in a

00:03:47.510 --> 00:03:50.020
certain way or vote
in a certain way.

00:03:50.020 --> 00:03:53.570
It's people who make music and
appreciate music, make art and

00:03:53.570 --> 00:03:57.616
appreciate art, read and write
literature, right?

00:03:57.616 --> 00:04:00.150
So in all these dimensions,
there's something very

00:04:00.150 --> 00:04:02.600
fundamental about what it is
about the human mind that

00:04:02.600 --> 00:04:07.560
gives birth to these areas of
inquiry and how those areas,

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:10.960
domains of human experience,
are enacted.

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:13.960
So my only goal today is to
try to convince you in a

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:18.490
number of different ways that
we're not simple video camera

00:04:18.490 --> 00:04:22.019
in our minds between our ears,
recording the world in some

00:04:22.019 --> 00:04:24.850
objective, simple way, that
even the simplest, most

00:04:24.850 --> 00:04:27.150
obvious things are
interpretations of the world

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:29.990
around us at many different
levels of thought and feeling

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:31.190
and perception.

00:04:31.190 --> 00:04:33.650
And then our minds, the way
our minds are constructed,

00:04:33.650 --> 00:04:36.610
determines the world that we
experience, that we see, that

00:04:36.610 --> 00:04:37.900
we act upon.

00:04:37.900 --> 00:04:39.930
And even very simple things
that we think are pretty

00:04:39.930 --> 00:04:42.370
objective and simple, right
in front of our eyes, are

00:04:42.370 --> 00:04:45.660
determined by inferences and
deductions that our mind

00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:48.560
makes, weighing sources of
evidence in the world and

00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:51.150
coming to conclusions about
what's around us, what we

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:53.970
hear, what we see,
and how we think.

00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:55.460
So let's start with seeing.

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:59.080
If your vision is reasonable,
we say we see something, we

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:01.180
believe it, right?

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:03.150
So let's start with something
very simple--

00:05:03.150 --> 00:05:04.200
these lines.

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:08.680
So one of the tough things about
psychology is ever since

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:11.550
the Internet came into
existence, people know every

00:05:11.550 --> 00:05:13.080
cool thing there is
to know, right?

00:05:13.080 --> 00:05:14.170
OK.

00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:17.120
I can tell you when I began
teaching, people said, oh my

00:05:17.120 --> 00:05:18.510
gosh, I've never seen
such a thing.

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:19.810
It's unbelievable!

00:05:19.810 --> 00:05:21.760
And then now, it's like two
thirds of the class is like,

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:24.640
yeah, I've got that on
my computer at home.

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:27.180
We did that in third
grade or whatever.

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:29.450
So all I'm saying is enjoy the
ones you haven't seen before,

00:05:29.450 --> 00:05:32.330
don't ruin it for your neighbors
today, because it's

00:05:32.330 --> 00:05:33.880
harder and harder to
surprise the world

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:35.070
in a nice way, right?

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:37.540
OK, but let's look at these
lines for a moment here.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:39.670
And perhaps you'll have the
sense, and maybe-- is it

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:40.910
glaring up there, sir?

00:05:40.910 --> 00:05:42.160
Let's see.

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:47.680
OK, is that better?

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:48.880
OK.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:50.120
Maybe not.

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:55.820
So you might have the sense that
this line is a different

00:05:55.820 --> 00:05:57.480
length than this line.

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:00.280
And this might be somewhere
intermediate, right?

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:03.690
Now you know, because of
psychology, it's all a trick.

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:06.010
But what's simpler than
the length of a line?

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:07.650
What's more objective
in some sense than

00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:08.370
the length of a line?

00:06:08.370 --> 00:06:10.710
But if we look at the actual
lengths, they're

00:06:10.710 --> 00:06:12.390
all literally identical.

00:06:12.390 --> 00:06:14.160
But that center part
looks different.

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:17.210
So what does it mean for
it to look different?

00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:19.800
It means our minds are
determining as simple a thing

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:22.300
as how long a line is depending
on the other

00:06:22.300 --> 00:06:23.680
information surrounding it.

00:06:23.680 --> 00:06:25.780
It's an interpretation
in context.

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:29.100
If we're simply looking, the
lines will look the same.

00:06:29.100 --> 00:06:31.730
Let's try another one.

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:35.122
It's remarkable that those two
lines are identical in length.

00:06:35.122 --> 00:06:36.046
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:36.046 --> 00:06:39.005
PROFESSOR: OK, all right.

00:06:39.005 --> 00:06:41.460
It's OK to test the limits
of the credibility of the

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:41.900
audience, right?

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:42.370
All right.

00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:42.870
Yeah.

00:06:42.870 --> 00:06:45.940
Of course, if our visual system
were ludicrously off,

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:49.220
we'd be constantly walking into
walls and falling out

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:51.000
windows and things like that,
right, if we were

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:52.530
misestimating at that length.

00:06:52.530 --> 00:06:54.570
So the idea where we have visual
illusions-- and I'll

00:06:54.570 --> 00:06:57.000
show you some more that I think
you'll be impressed by--

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.470
it's not that our visual system
is messed up or that

00:07:00.470 --> 00:07:02.920
psychologists think it's
hilarious to trick us.

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:06.100
It's that lots of things our
visual system is a brilliant

00:07:06.100 --> 00:07:09.010
at, but it's brilliant by
having certain laws or

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:11.000
principles that it follows.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.060
And we can show this following
those principles by seeing

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:17.380
that when we mess with the
typical circumstances, those

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:20.210
principles calculate
the wrong answer.

00:07:20.210 --> 00:07:21.600
So here's another one.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:24.850
So, to most people, which line
looks bigger, the one in the

00:07:24.850 --> 00:07:27.970
middle or the one on the side?

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:29.420
I know you know it's
all a trick, right?

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:31.490
OK.

00:07:31.490 --> 00:07:33.480
What could be more obvious
than that this is longer?

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:36.480
It's just a simple line, but if
we draw red lines on top of

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:39.940
it then move them over here,
they're dead identical.

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:40.980
The central circle--

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:42.540
does one of them, the
middle circle, look

00:07:42.540 --> 00:07:44.160
larger than the other?

00:07:44.160 --> 00:07:47.380
Now you already know,
intellectually, that it will

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:49.915
turn out those two circles in
the middle will be the same.

00:07:49.915 --> 00:07:52.840
But you have to convince
yourself that it still looks

00:07:52.840 --> 00:07:53.830
like they're different.

00:07:53.830 --> 00:07:54.610
Here there in red.

00:07:54.610 --> 00:07:55.800
Here they are next
to each other.

00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:56.690
They're identical.

00:07:56.690 --> 00:07:59.170
Again, this is evidence that,
even for a simple thing like

00:07:59.170 --> 00:08:02.210
the size of a circle, your mind
is making inferences.

00:08:02.210 --> 00:08:05.110
And there are principles and
laws that it's following that

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:08.090
determine what it is you
think that you see.

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.140
Here is two monsters
chasing each other.

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:12.990
But in fact, they're
identical in size.

00:08:12.990 --> 00:08:15.890
The perspective cues make
the more distant

00:08:15.890 --> 00:08:18.860
one look much bigger.

00:08:18.860 --> 00:08:19.910
This is from Ted Adelson.

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:24.150
This is a beautiful
demonstration of an illusion.

00:08:24.150 --> 00:08:27.560
Ted Adelson's in the psychology
department.

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:29.280
There's a letter A here.

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:30.810
And believe it or not, there's
a letter B there.

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:33.440
Let's see if this looks any
better when it goes like this.

00:08:33.440 --> 00:08:35.440
It doesn't.

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:36.120
All right.

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:38.700
So one of the important things
about illusions,

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:40.500
demonstrations in this class--
and you will learn this as we

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:43.010
go along-- is occasionally they
fail, and we come back

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:44.780
and discover what the
lesson of that is.

00:08:44.780 --> 00:08:47.110
So I'm just telling you
it's showing you on my

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:48.070
monitor much brighter.

00:08:48.070 --> 00:08:49.910
It always has before.

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:51.450
We'll adjust that.

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:53.060
So I'm going to skip this, but
I'll show you another time,

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:55.360
because it's so good.

00:08:55.360 --> 00:08:57.060
And I'm going to feel
bad about this.

00:08:57.060 --> 00:08:58.050
OK.

00:08:58.050 --> 00:09:01.480
Now, let's see.

00:09:01.480 --> 00:09:02.730
This'll work.

00:09:10.690 --> 00:09:12.035
All the same shade
of grey, right?

00:09:28.312 --> 00:09:29.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:29.780 --> 00:09:33.070
PROFESSOR: Did that work
reasonably from where you sat?

00:09:33.070 --> 00:09:36.150
We'll try a few more.

00:09:36.150 --> 00:09:37.400
Maybe.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:42.180
For some reason,
my connection's

00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:43.430
always like this, sorry.

00:10:05.956 --> 00:10:07.940
Does that one look lighter
than that one that way?

00:10:07.940 --> 00:10:09.190
Yeah.

00:10:36.212 --> 00:10:38.000
Now they look radically
different, right?

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:39.870
It's the same grey constantly.

00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:43.720
But again, the context is hugely
determining how to

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:44.980
bright you see that grey.

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:46.230
There it is.

00:11:09.026 --> 00:11:11.516
Two boxes equal grey.

00:11:26.460 --> 00:11:29.400
So things as simple as how
bright something is or how

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:34.380
long something is depend
on interpretation.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:38.430
Here's an illusion from
Roger Shepard.

00:11:38.430 --> 00:11:39.460
It's kind of great.

00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:40.990
So here's two kind of different

00:11:40.990 --> 00:11:42.580
looking tables, right?

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:43.840
But they're not that
different.

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:45.800
And watch.

00:11:45.800 --> 00:11:47.050
There goes one tabletop.

00:11:55.320 --> 00:11:59.490
You're not impressed that those
are identical tables?

00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:00.000
OK.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:01.250
Want me to do it again?

00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:08.480
That's the identical tabletop.

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:10.590
To me, the one on the left looks
pretty rectangular and

00:12:10.590 --> 00:12:11.990
the one on the right looks
pretty square-ish.

00:12:16.650 --> 00:12:17.880
You're not easy to
impress, are you?

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:23.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:23.100 --> 00:12:25.220
PROFESSOR: You see that those
two bars are moving together

00:12:25.220 --> 00:12:25.990
at the same time.

00:12:25.990 --> 00:12:28.670
Does it look like they're
little steps?

00:12:28.670 --> 00:12:29.890
It'll show you.

00:12:29.890 --> 00:12:31.140
All right, fine.

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:36.750
It's just like that, but
now you add those bars.

00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:37.800
Does it look like little steps?

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:44.900
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:48.340
PROFESSOR: One more
of this kind.

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:49.590
This is kind of fun.

00:12:56.070 --> 00:12:58.500
You see the way that the
mask is turning?

00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:03.920
It always looks like it's
towards you, even though I'm--

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:05.480
one of the rotations-- it's
because of the way you're

00:13:05.480 --> 00:13:07.840
interpreting the light is
influencing how you

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:08.890
interpreting what's--

00:13:08.890 --> 00:13:10.570
OK.

00:13:10.570 --> 00:13:15.000
So that's simply a consequence,
as far as people

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.030
understand that, that the source
of the illumination is

00:13:18.030 --> 00:13:20.790
not where you're used to, so
you're misinterpreting where

00:13:20.790 --> 00:13:23.120
the illumination is coming
from for the depth of the

00:13:23.120 --> 00:13:25.260
face, what's front and what's
back, whether the nose is

00:13:25.260 --> 00:13:26.510
sticking in or sticking out.

00:13:29.850 --> 00:13:31.100
OK.

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:39.600
So again, the point in these
illusions is, even for very

00:13:39.600 --> 00:13:42.410
simple things our, minds make
certain assumptions about how

00:13:42.410 --> 00:13:44.040
we interpret the world.

