In fact, it goes to 70%.

00:36:41.310 --> 00:36:43.380
And if it's 24 people,
it's 50%.

00:36:43.380 --> 00:36:45.860
If you're a group of 36 people,
there's a 90% chance,

00:36:45.860 --> 00:36:47.190
just mathematically, that
two people will

00:36:47.190 --> 00:36:48.840
share the same birthday.

00:36:48.840 --> 00:36:53.070
Because when we face things that
are hard to think about,

00:36:53.070 --> 00:36:56.190
because there's no easy answer,
humans tend to take

00:36:56.190 --> 00:37:00.180
shortcuts and say, what's the
gist of my experience, and

00:37:00.180 --> 00:37:01.430
that's what I think
the answer is.

00:37:01.430 --> 00:37:04.700
Even when a calculable
answer is available.

00:37:04.700 --> 00:37:07.580
It's human nature to make a
shortcut based on your sense

00:37:07.580 --> 00:37:08.830
of your experience.

00:37:10.900 --> 00:37:15.560
So there's a very interesting
line of work--

00:37:15.560 --> 00:37:18.040
Dan Gilbert of Harvard
is a leading figure--

00:37:18.040 --> 00:37:20.910
about this idea of thinking
about your future.

00:37:20.910 --> 00:37:23.780
Now, thinking about our future
is a big thing, right?

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:27.580
We're thinking about what's it
like in this course, what's it

00:37:27.580 --> 00:37:30.090
like in college, what's our
friendship like, relations

00:37:30.090 --> 00:37:32.790
with parents, what's our future
career paths, what kind

00:37:32.790 --> 00:37:34.670
of life will we lead, right?

00:37:34.670 --> 00:37:37.690
Our future is something that's
hugely on our mind, I think,

00:37:37.690 --> 00:37:39.860
very powerfully when you're
a college student

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:40.530
or a graduate student.

00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:42.110
What's my future?

00:37:42.110 --> 00:37:44.680
And a big question that people
have is what will make me

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:46.170
happy in a deep sense?

00:37:46.170 --> 00:37:48.270
What will make me happy
in a deep sense?

00:37:48.270 --> 00:37:50.010
Because that's the life
I want to lead--

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:52.620
the values I want to have, the
kind of career choices and

00:37:52.620 --> 00:37:55.950
personal choices I want to make,
where I will devote my

00:37:55.950 --> 00:37:58.340
time on this earth.

00:37:58.340 --> 00:38:02.820
So most people, first of all,
tend to think about good

00:38:02.820 --> 00:38:04.550
things, positive things.

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:06.430
Actually, I can tell you what
comes later in the course.

00:38:06.430 --> 00:38:07.660
It's good to think that lots of

00:38:07.660 --> 00:38:08.640
positive things are happening.

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:10.050
It's kind of a nice place
to be in terms of

00:38:10.050 --> 00:38:12.230
being a happy person.

00:38:12.230 --> 00:38:17.350
But it turns out that people
have done studies like this.

00:38:17.350 --> 00:38:20.380
So now this is particularly
sensitive for a faculty

00:38:20.380 --> 00:38:22.880
member, but it could work for
any sports team you've tried

00:38:22.880 --> 00:38:25.090
out or anything you've tried
out for in your life.

00:38:25.090 --> 00:38:27.010
So what happens when we get
reviewed for tenure?

00:38:27.010 --> 00:38:28.410
And you hear a bit about that.

00:38:28.410 --> 00:38:31.340
This was an easy study for
a psychologist to do.

00:38:31.340 --> 00:38:34.190
What they did is they called up
people in the fall who were

00:38:34.190 --> 00:38:36.260
being reviewed for tenure.

00:38:36.260 --> 00:38:38.670
And you get tenure
or you don't.

00:38:38.670 --> 00:38:40.935
And it's a bit of a sad process
if you don't, right,

00:38:40.935 --> 00:38:43.150
because you don't get tenure,
and then you don't feel happy

00:38:43.150 --> 00:38:43.690
about that.

00:38:43.690 --> 00:38:45.230
And you have to call your
parents and say, I didn't get

00:38:45.230 --> 00:38:47.220
tenure, and your parents go,
come on, if you just slept

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:48.340
better, you would've
gotten tenure.

00:38:48.340 --> 00:38:50.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:50.150 --> 00:38:54.570
PROFESSOR: Remember the piano
lessons you didn't take.

00:38:54.570 --> 00:38:56.220
So it's a bit of a
nuisance, right?

00:38:56.220 --> 00:38:57.290
On top of that--

00:38:57.290 --> 00:38:59.420
because weirdly, in academics,
we tend to be super

00:38:59.420 --> 00:39:01.940
specialized-- you have
to move out of town.

00:39:01.940 --> 00:39:04.500
You don't have to, but
typically, a person who

00:39:04.500 --> 00:39:06.500
doesn't get tenure will get
a job somewhere else.

00:39:06.500 --> 00:39:08.620
There's plenty of stories of
people who don't get tenure at

00:39:08.620 --> 00:39:11.690
awesome places who were
geniuses in history.

00:39:11.690 --> 00:39:13.600
The tenure decisions
are often wrong.

00:39:13.600 --> 00:39:15.520
But still, you'd rather
get it than not.

00:39:15.520 --> 00:39:17.660
You'd rather get into the
medical school than not.

00:39:17.660 --> 00:39:18.970
You'd rather make a sports
team you want

00:39:18.970 --> 00:39:21.210
to be on than not.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:22.410
So here's what they found out.

00:39:22.410 --> 00:39:24.900
If they asked them what happens
if you don't get

00:39:24.900 --> 00:39:26.400
tenure, everybody says, oh,
it's gonna be awful.

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:27.335
It's gonna be miserable.

00:39:27.335 --> 00:39:29.440
I'm gonna be such an
unhappy person.

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:33.570
Two years later, the average
happiness of people who didn't

00:39:33.570 --> 00:39:36.200
get tenure was equal to the
average happiness of people

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:38.220
who did get tenure.

00:39:38.220 --> 00:39:39.970
So you can say, well,
tenure-- only

00:39:39.970 --> 00:39:41.420
professors care about tenure.

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:43.530
Well, how about winning
the lottery?

00:39:43.530 --> 00:39:45.510
What if I won hundreds of
thousands of dollars?

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:48.470
There' been a lot of psychology
on this, actually.

00:39:48.470 --> 00:39:52.360
In about a year to two, the
average happiness of a lottery

00:39:52.360 --> 00:39:54.560
winner who won a substantial
amount of money is rated the

00:39:54.560 --> 00:39:58.670
same by him or her as it was
the population as a whole.

00:39:58.670 --> 00:39:59.050
Yeah?

00:39:59.050 --> 00:40:00.394
AUDIENCE: How did they go about

00:40:00.394 --> 00:40:01.740
measuring average happiness?

00:40:01.740 --> 00:40:03.050
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so we'll
come back to this,

00:40:03.050 --> 00:40:04.860
but I'll tell you.

00:40:04.860 --> 00:40:06.870
You can like this or
not like this.

00:40:06.870 --> 00:40:08.820
In some parts of psychology,
we measure things like

00:40:08.820 --> 00:40:10.220
reaction time to the
millisecond.

00:40:10.220 --> 00:40:12.410
That's good data, right?

00:40:12.410 --> 00:40:14.930
Our brain activation,
that's good data.

00:40:14.930 --> 00:40:17.480
When you ask a person how happy
they are, the only thing

00:40:17.480 --> 00:40:19.670
we can do is have you basically
fill a scale from

00:40:19.670 --> 00:40:20.360
one to seven.

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:22.250
How happy are you?

00:40:22.250 --> 00:40:24.190
And you could go, well I'm a
little worried about that,

00:40:24.190 --> 00:40:26.650
because sometimes people say, I
hope that it makes you happy

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:27.820
or something.

00:40:27.820 --> 00:40:30.290
So you could say, how
much can we trust

00:40:30.290 --> 00:40:31.780
subjective reports of happiness?

00:40:31.780 --> 00:40:33.290
And that's a very
good question.

00:40:33.290 --> 00:40:35.150
On the other hand, it's hard
to know what would

00:40:35.150 --> 00:40:37.660
be better than that.

00:40:37.660 --> 00:40:39.080
If we measure your
pulse, is that a

00:40:39.080 --> 00:40:41.840
better measure of happiness?

00:40:41.840 --> 00:40:43.830
Your pulse could be racing
because you're sad or happy,

00:40:43.830 --> 00:40:45.650
scared or enthusiastic.

00:40:45.650 --> 00:40:48.280
So we don't have a better one
that we can think of.

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:50.330
But psychologists do worry that
sometimes people will

00:40:50.330 --> 00:40:51.990
just say what they're
supposed to say.

00:40:51.990 --> 00:40:54.350
Or they'll pretend they're happy
or things like that.

00:40:54.350 --> 00:40:56.890
We have to worry about
those things.

00:40:56.890 --> 00:40:59.890
So you could worry deep down,
but a year or two later,

00:40:59.890 --> 00:41:02.260
people who win huge amounts of
money don't report themselves

00:41:02.260 --> 00:41:05.930
as any happier than people
around them.

00:41:05.930 --> 00:41:07.050
And kind of amazingly--

00:41:07.050 --> 00:41:10.120
but I think it's deep
about life--

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:12.460
accidents leading to
quadriplegia or paraplegia,

00:41:12.460 --> 00:41:16.260
accidents that, before you had
such an accident you would

00:41:16.260 --> 00:41:20.220
imagine that it would be
something extremely difficult.

00:41:20.220 --> 00:41:21.670
And it can be in many ways.

00:41:21.670 --> 00:41:26.370
But by self report, ratings of
happiness return to typical

00:41:26.370 --> 00:41:28.170
average populations
of the same age

00:41:28.170 --> 00:41:29.940
in about three months.

00:41:29.940 --> 00:41:32.860
So what's a huge lesson here
in happiness research--

00:41:32.860 --> 00:41:33.610
a huge surprise.

00:41:33.610 --> 00:41:34.970
It's two things.

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:37.670
We're kind of bad at predicting
what will make us

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:40.330
happy or sad, which is
kind of weird, right?

00:41:40.330 --> 00:41:42.260
We're kind of bad at
predicting it.

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:44.220
Here's all these things where
we think they would make us

00:41:44.220 --> 00:41:45.920
happy or make us not so happy.

00:41:45.920 --> 00:41:49.810
It turns out we're wrong when
this is studied at all

00:41:49.810 --> 00:41:52.570
scientifically.

00:41:52.570 --> 00:41:54.840
So we'll come back to that later
on, because it's a very

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:56.810
deep thing about
being a human--

00:41:56.810 --> 00:41:59.660
what makes you happy and
your wrong guesses

00:41:59.660 --> 00:42:01.300
sometimes about what does.

00:42:01.300 --> 00:42:03.390
So let me end with a
last experiment.

00:42:03.390 --> 00:42:06.610
So we've really haven't done
experiments until right now.

00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:10.210
And this is now a sensitive and
difficult issue, which is

00:42:10.210 --> 00:42:13.230
problems we have in dealing
with racism.

00:42:13.230 --> 00:42:15.250
And here's a study that
did the following.

00:42:15.250 --> 00:42:18.140
It said, well, in North America,
certainly, Canada,

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:20.590
the US-- a study was
done in Canada--

00:42:20.590 --> 00:42:24.370
racism is widely condemned,
as I think most of us

00:42:24.370 --> 00:42:26.440
believe it should be.

00:42:26.440 --> 00:42:29.070
But examples of blatant
racism still occurred.

00:42:29.070 --> 00:42:32.330
One recent poll said that
about a third of white

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:34.760
individuals reported hearing
anti-black slurs in the

00:42:34.760 --> 00:42:36.830
workplace in the last
couple years--

00:42:36.830 --> 00:42:38.000
to pick one thing.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:41.730
So how does this happen in a
society that speaks so much

00:42:41.730 --> 00:42:45.010
about not being racist, about
treating everybody equally and

00:42:45.010 --> 00:42:46.370
fairly and kindly?

00:42:46.370 --> 00:42:47.800
How does it happen that
we still struggle.

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:50.380
And it's such a very deep,
difficult question about human

00:42:50.380 --> 00:42:52.660
nature and the world
we live in.

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:55.910
But here's something again
that's a hint about why it's

00:42:55.910 --> 00:43:00.150
hard to get society to change
some of its behaviors.

00:43:00.150 --> 00:43:01.590
So here's the experiment--

00:43:01.590 --> 00:43:03.110
so it's an actual experiment.

00:43:03.110 --> 00:43:07.160
So they took two groups of
college undergraduates and

00:43:07.160 --> 00:43:09.890
randomly assigned one to be
in the forecaster group.

00:43:09.890 --> 00:43:12.890
That's a group that tells you
how they think they would feel

00:43:12.890 --> 00:43:15.280
and how they think they would
act under certain

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:17.380
circumstances.

00:43:17.380 --> 00:43:19.320
And then an experiencer
group--

00:43:19.320 --> 00:43:21.640
that's a group who actually
undergoes an experience, and

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:24.080
I'll tell you what
that is now.

00:43:24.080 --> 00:43:26.550
So in the experiencer group,
pretend you were their

00:43:26.550 --> 00:43:27.350
research participant.

00:43:27.350 --> 00:43:31.010
You walk into a room, and you
see in that room a black male

00:43:31.010 --> 00:43:31.630
and a white male.

00:43:31.630 --> 00:43:34.770
Now those two are what
psychologists, for some

00:43:34.770 --> 00:43:36.300
reason, have called
confederates.

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:37.460
Those are role players.

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:40.530
They know what they're doing.

00:43:40.530 --> 00:43:41.830
They have a plan of what
they're going to do.

00:43:41.830 --> 00:43:43.640
They're going to put on
a little show for you.

00:43:43.640 --> 00:43:46.030
But you don't know that.

00:43:46.030 --> 00:43:48.930
And the black male stands up and
leaves the room to get his

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:51.770
cell phone, and he gently bumps
the white male's knee.

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:52.810
This is all set up.

00:43:52.810 --> 00:43:55.120
You're just sitting there and
you see that little bump.

00:43:55.120 --> 00:43:58.460
And now, there's three
different groups.

00:43:58.460 --> 00:43:59.550
One group, that's it.

00:43:59.550 --> 00:44:00.490
Nothing else happens--

00:44:00.490 --> 00:44:02.860
A small bump, and the
person leaves.

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:04.790
A second group--

00:44:04.790 --> 00:44:07.620
as you sit there, the black
individual leaves the room and

00:44:07.620 --> 00:44:10.530
the white individual says,
quote, "Typical, I hate it

00:44:10.530 --> 00:44:12.710
when black people do that."
It's meant to be obviously

00:44:12.710 --> 00:44:14.900
provocative and racist.

00:44:14.900 --> 00:44:17.530
And then what they consider
an extreme slur--

00:44:17.530 --> 00:44:20.370
the white person in the room
playing this role uses the

00:44:20.370 --> 00:44:25.380
derogatory word that's meant
to be an extreme slur.

00:44:25.380 --> 00:44:28.950
So there's one more thing
you need to know.

00:44:28.950 --> 00:44:30.750
Now, you're sitting there, and
you're either in the control

00:44:30.750 --> 00:44:33.730
group where there's been the
slight bump, or there's been a

00:44:33.730 --> 00:44:37.340
moderate slur, or an extreme
slur in their words.

00:44:37.340 --> 00:44:38.360
The black male returns.

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:40.660
Don't forget, he's in on it,
and so is that white male.

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:41.470
But you're not in on it.

00:44:41.470 --> 00:44:43.680
You just think there was a bump,
and something else may

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:46.480
have happened, depending on
which condition you're in.

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:48.680
And the experimenter then gives
you a survey about how

00:44:48.680 --> 00:44:50.650
you feel right now.

00:44:50.650 --> 00:44:52.110
Sort of like the happiness,
but it's not that.

00:44:52.110 --> 00:44:53.860
It's like, how do you
feel right now?

00:44:53.860 --> 00:44:56.720
And then asks you to pick
between those two people a

00:44:56.720 --> 00:44:59.110
partner for an anagram
experiment that

00:44:59.110 --> 00:45:01.220
you're about to do.

00:45:01.220 --> 00:45:02.970
So they're going to ask you--

00:45:02.970 --> 00:45:04.770
this is sort of this
question you have.

00:45:04.770 --> 00:45:07.810
What's the difference or
similarity between what you

00:45:07.810 --> 00:45:10.650
say you're feeling is and
what you really do?

00:45:10.650 --> 00:45:12.600
Both things are important,
but do they line up, do

00:45:12.600 --> 00:45:13.720
they not line up?

00:45:13.720 --> 00:45:15.300
So here's the results.

00:45:15.300 --> 00:45:16.080
Here's a graph.

00:45:16.080 --> 00:45:17.690
And here's how this works.

00:45:17.690 --> 00:45:20.650
Negative emotional distress the
higher the bar, the more

00:45:20.650 --> 00:45:23.900
you say, I feel really bad about
what's just happened.

00:45:23.900 --> 00:45:26.300
I just heard this comment
or no comment.

00:45:26.300 --> 00:45:28.000
So let's take a look,
the higher the bar.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:31.390
If you heard no comment,
here's how you begin.

00:45:31.390 --> 00:45:33.800
So let's start with
the forecasters.

00:45:33.800 --> 00:45:35.555
All of you are forecasters,
because you're pretending

00:45:35.555 --> 00:45:38.210
you're in the situation
but you're not in it.

00:45:38.210 --> 00:45:40.250
So here is there was
no comments.

00:45:40.250 --> 00:45:41.910
That's sort of average
or something.

00:45:41.910 --> 00:45:44.440
And then you said if you
heard a racial slur

00:45:44.440 --> 00:45:46.554
you would feel terrible.

00:45:46.554 --> 00:45:49.920
You would feel terrible.

00:45:49.920 --> 00:45:52.480
But look at the other students
who are randomly picked.

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:54.720
So we don't think it's a
difference among students.

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:55.500
Look at these grey bars.

00:45:55.500 --> 00:45:57.950
They're pretty flat.

00:45:57.950 --> 00:46:02.560
The person on the spot is
somehow not processing this.

00:46:02.560 --> 00:46:06.140
And they're filling out,
I feel average.

00:46:06.140 --> 00:46:08.030
You see the split--

00:46:08.030 --> 00:46:11.310
the split between the values
that the person thinks they

00:46:11.310 --> 00:46:14.200
would have, and the values that
are responded to on the

00:46:14.200 --> 00:46:16.370
spot in the moment.

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:18.410
And what we'll talk about later
on in social psychology

00:46:18.410 --> 00:46:23.860
is there's a tough gap, often,
between the values we espouse

00:46:23.860 --> 00:46:26.500
and how we act when there's
especially unexpected,

00:46:26.500 --> 00:46:27.900
difficult things.

00:46:27.900 --> 00:46:29.340
And very often--

00:46:29.340 --> 00:46:31.130
if you've had any experience
like this-- afterwards, you

00:46:31.130 --> 00:46:32.890
go, oh, what I should
have done is this.

00:46:32.890 --> 00:46:34.730
Or I wish I would've
said that.

00:46:34.730 --> 00:46:37.040
But that moment is not happening
at that moment,

00:46:37.040 --> 00:46:38.250
probably because you're
kind of weirded out

00:46:38.250 --> 00:46:38.910
by the whole thing.

00:46:38.910 --> 00:46:39.670
What's going on?

00:46:39.670 --> 00:46:41.810
Why would the person say this?

00:46:41.810 --> 00:46:42.620
Something doesn't seem right.

00:46:42.620 --> 00:46:44.330
I can't sort it out.

00:46:44.330 --> 00:46:47.900
And so people tend to shrink
in terms of making a strong

00:46:47.900 --> 00:46:50.060
conclusion of what's going on
if something seems unusually

00:46:50.060 --> 00:46:51.140
provocative.

00:46:51.140 --> 00:46:53.010
And you could say, well, OK,
that's their attitudes.

00:46:53.010 --> 00:46:53.860
But how about their action?

00:46:53.860 --> 00:46:55.670
Who do they pick to
be their partner?

00:46:55.670 --> 00:46:58.340
And again, the people
forecasting said, if I was in

00:46:58.340 --> 00:47:04.550
this situation, I would never
pick that racist white person

00:47:04.550 --> 00:47:08.570
to be my partner, because
that person stinks--

00:47:08.570 --> 00:47:10.120
if I was in that situation.

00:47:10.120 --> 00:47:12.720
But if the people are
in the situation--

00:47:12.720 --> 00:47:14.180
look at the grey bars--

00:47:14.180 --> 00:47:15.440
pretty flat.

00:47:15.440 --> 00:47:19.620
It's a if on the spot, in the
moment, they can't quite

00:47:19.620 --> 00:47:22.730
process the values they
feel and the action

00:47:22.730 --> 00:47:24.130
they're going to take.

00:47:24.130 --> 00:47:25.260
And we'll talk about that.

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:28.870
And it's very hard, often,
in part, to be brave

00:47:28.870 --> 00:47:29.810
and stand up to things.

00:47:29.810 --> 00:47:31.670
It turns out there's a lot
of evidence for this.

00:47:31.670 --> 00:47:33.900
It's a human nature thing.

00:47:33.900 --> 00:47:36.090
It's very hard to be brave and
stand up to things when things

00:47:36.090 --> 00:47:38.140
are kind of weird, because
almost everybody at first

00:47:38.140 --> 00:47:40.180
thinks, I don't want to
make a fool of myself.

00:47:40.180 --> 00:47:41.830
I don't want make trouble.

00:47:41.830 --> 00:47:43.880
Maybe I'm not getting the
whole picture on this.

00:47:43.880 --> 00:47:47.080
And we shrink back from acting
in a way that aligns with the

00:47:47.080 --> 00:47:51.900
values that are clearly
shown here.

00:47:51.900 --> 00:47:53.520
So this, again, is something
about human

00:47:53.520 --> 00:47:54.610
nature that's very weird.

00:47:54.610 --> 00:47:56.260
And it's powerful to come
into social psychology.

00:47:56.260 --> 00:47:59.050
And that's why it's very hard
to stand up to things like

00:47:59.050 --> 00:48:00.210
oppression and bias.

00:48:00.210 --> 00:48:04.240
It's very hard to do, because
we tend to not act on our

00:48:04.240 --> 00:48:05.910
values when we're
in complicated

00:48:05.910 --> 00:48:08.730
situations on the spot.

00:48:08.730 --> 00:48:10.920
And there's a tremendous amount
of evidence for that.

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:12.990
So again, how we interpret
the situation--

00:48:12.990 --> 00:48:16.880
very different in our mind when
we imagine we're there,

00:48:16.880 --> 00:48:17.890
and when we actually
sit there.

00:48:17.890 --> 00:48:20.710
And so what these researchers
say is this is partly why it's

00:48:20.710 --> 00:48:25.350
been hard to eradicate some
vestiges of stereotypes and

00:48:25.350 --> 00:48:29.160
racism, because people have a
hard time clamping down on it

00:48:29.160 --> 00:48:30.410
in the moment.

00:48:33.170 --> 00:48:35.580
So that's a tough topic, but we
know we want to deal both

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:38.650
with things that are less
controversial but also things

00:48:38.650 --> 00:48:40.580
that touch people's lives
in the real world

00:48:40.580 --> 00:48:41.480
that we live in.

00:48:41.480 --> 00:48:43.320
So we talked about a
scientific study

00:48:43.320 --> 00:48:44.490
of the human nature--

00:48:44.490 --> 00:48:45.770
mind and behavior--

00:48:45.770 --> 00:48:50.740
how what we see and hear is
determined so much but how our

00:48:50.740 --> 00:48:53.240
mind interprets the world around
us; how we remember

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:55.330
things like word lists or
stories, that's hugely

00:48:55.330 --> 00:48:58.800
influenced by what we expect to
see, like in the picture;

00:48:58.800 --> 00:49:01.670
how we think we know things like
where Reno is compared to

00:49:01.670 --> 00:49:04.450
San Francisco; how we think
about things like the

00:49:04.450 --> 00:49:06.990
probability that somebody else
will have the same birthday,

00:49:06.990 --> 00:49:10.150
that somebody else will in a
group; and the relationship

00:49:10.150 --> 00:49:12.390
between how we feel
and how we act.

00:49:12.390 --> 00:49:15.530
The very feelings we have are
often disconnected for actions

00:49:15.530 --> 00:49:16.900
in the moment.

00:49:16.900 --> 00:49:19.980
And sometimes that has a sort
of a difficult consequence.

00:49:19.980 --> 00:49:22.100
And so we'll explore all these
things through the semester,

00:49:22.100 --> 00:49:24.005
all the different facets that we
could possibly get through

00:49:24.005 --> 00:49:26.680
in one semester of what it is to
be human, and where science

00:49:26.680 --> 00:49:28.710
has showed us something about
human nature, the

00:49:28.710 --> 00:49:29.960
mind, and the brain.

